article.description:
Rod Strickland is finally getting into
playing shape, and the Minnesota Timberwolves are reaping the
rewards.
article.headline: Garnett's big second half leads T-Wolves over Rockets
article.linkText: Strickland keeps T-Wolves calm in win over Rockets
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Rod Strickland is finally getting into playing shape, and the Minnesota Timberwolves are reaping the rewards.
Strickland

Garnett

Strickland had 14 points and seven assists, but more importantly kept the team calm and got Kevin Garnett involved when the Timberwolves needed him most. Troy Hudson hit five 3-pointers in the first half and Garnett dominated the second half as the Timberwolves ended Houston's three-game winning streak with a 98-86 victory Saturday night. Garnett had 27 points, 11 rebounds and five assists. He scored 13 of Minnesota's 21 points in the third quarter, then combined with Gary Trent for 16 points in the fourth as the Wolves used a 16-7 run over the last 8:47 to close out the win. Steve Francis led the Rockets with 24 points and Yao Ming finished with 12 points and 12 rebounds after struggling in the first half. The Timberwolves signed Strickland as Troy Hudson's backup to help provide the veteran leadership Terrell Brandon once did. Brandon underwent major knee surgery in February and is on the injured list. "I'm feeling better in my conditioning and a lot more comfortable on the court,'' Strickland said. Both Garnett and coach Flip Saunders credited Strickland with keeping the team composed after an 18-point first-half lead evaporated into a one-point deficit late in the third quarter. "Rod, when he's getting his legs together more, makes good decisions and calms us down a lot,'' Saunders said. The Timberwolves raced out to an early lead by shooting 57 percent from the field in the first quarter, including four 3-pointers by Hudson. A 13-0 run gave the Wolves a 30-20 lead after one. The lead ballooned to 18 midway through the second quarter before Houston started a comeback, closing to 50-43 with two minutes to play in the half. But after sitting for much of the second quarter, Hudson picked up where he left off, hitting a fallaway 3-pointer from the corner with 1:25 left to push the lead back to 10, 53-43. Houston used superior work on the offensive boards and capitalized on poor shooting by the Timberwolves to get back into the game in the third quarter. After being outplayed by Rasho Nesterovic for much of the first half, Yao started to assert himself. The No. 1 pick in this year's draft grabbed six rebounds and scored six points in the quarter, and his two free throws with 3 minutes left in the quarter gave the Rockets a 67-66 lead, their first since they led 2-0 early in the game. Strickland knew what to do. He started running the offense almost exclusively through Garnett, and the move paid dividends. "Rod looks for me a lot, probably too much sometimes,'' Garnett said. Garnett, who has been criticized for disappearing late in games, scored 21 points and had eight rebounds in the second half. "I do want the ball every time,'' Garnett said. "I knew I had to be a lot more aggressive in the second half with the ball and I had to get to the basket.'' He was, and he did, thanks in part to Strickland. "Rod stayed aggressive, and that helped things,'' Saunders said. "He got our players the ball in better spots, and we got better shots. That was the key.'' Yao said he was impressed with the way Garnett controlled the game when he needed to. "He seems like a spider,'' Yao said. "Strong arms, strong legs.'' Trent had 12 points and 13 rebounds for Minnesota. Game notes
Coach Flip Saunders said injured G Wally Szczerbiak had another X-ray on his toe Friday, which will be evaluated Monday by team doctors. ... Hudson's five 3-pointers in the first half were one short of James Robinson's team record for 3-pointers in a half. ... Glen Rice appeared to hit a buzzer-beating 3-pointer to end the third quarter, but after reviewing the play, the officials determined he did not get the shot off in time. ... James Posey, acquired by Houston in a three-way trade Wednesday, played two minutes at the end of the game and did not score.
